<TEXT>
the coast guard has begun searching the waters 
near the virgin islands for a 77yearold british noblewoman missing 
with the small airplane she was piloting federal authorities said 
thursday night 
mary pomeroy was flying a piper 28 aircraft from the dutchfrench 
island of st martin to st croix in the us virgin islands when 
her plane disappeared tuesday said fred farrar a spokesman for the 
federal aviation administration 
a piper 28 is a singleengine plane and the distance from st 
martin to st croix is about 100 miles 
farrar said details were sketchy but it was believed that ms 
pomeroy was countess of malta or duchess of malta in the british 
nobility the name of a place attached to a title does not have to 
be in britain 
however reference books on the british nobility list her only as 
the sister of thomas de vautort pomeroy 10th viscount of harberton 
the reference material gives her home as the isle of wight 
ms pomeroy was alone in the airplane when it left st martin 
about 305 pm tuesday flying under visual flight rules farrar 
said she radioed about seven minutes later that she was in level 
flight at about 4500 feet and that was the last transmission from 
the plane 
a squall line had been reported between st martin and st croix 
about that time farrar said 
the search for ms pomeroy did not begin until wednesday because 
it was initially reported that she had turned back to st martin 
farrar said 
coast guard helicopters a c130 airplane and a cutter searched 
an area about 40 miles from st martin but found nothing he said 
</TEXT>
