<TEXT>
debra gilbert was in her nightgown fixing 
breakfast when an ax broke through the front door as a dozen police 
officers waving shotguns swarmed her house she heard her husband 
yell she doesnt know anything she doesnt know 
what she didnt know was that her husband of four years was 
connected to the mob she didnt know he had killed three times and 
she didnt know the shambles her life would become 
yet even after she knew she stood by him when he agreed to 
testify against organized crime buddies living a bizarre life of 
fear that included time in a threeroom police station apartment 
she watched as her husband manipulated authorities serving his 
murder sentence while living the high life complete with 
thousanddollar expense accounts and beach house vacations when 
peter gilbert died of a heart attack in june 1988 he still was in 
custody but was driving alone to go skydiving in a buick stocked 
with cocaine 
i know a lot of people out there would say boy shes the 
biggest fool who ever walked this earth mrs gilbert said in an 
interview at her brooksville fla home but how many people can 
say they loved someone enough to love them blindly 
the case of peter gilbert offers an unusual glimpse into the 
sometimes peculiar world of crime and punishment where a man so 
skilled in manipulation can take not only his wife for a ride but 
also police and prosecutors 
his escapade rocked providences police department and led gov 
edward d diprete to order a state police investigation fourteen 
officers face disciplinary action for unprofessional conduct and a 
special prosecutor was named april 30 to take the case to a grand 
jury for possible criminal indictments 
a state judge is even considering overturning a conviction that 
was based on peter gilberts testimony because of all the lies 
the fiasco as the internal investigation calls it is 
expected to cost nearly 1 million by the time all the probes are 
completed 
then the state of rhode island and especially myself will be 
able to put pieces together and not feel like there is anything 
missing anymore mrs gilbert said 
a consummate con man peter gilbert made up in charisma what he 
lacked in conscience he told debra their marriage was his first 
when it was at least his fifth standing 5 feet 5 inches with a 
scruffy beard and tattoos peter hardly seemed the ladys man debra 
knew he had children but she wasnt one to ask a lot of questions 
when they met in florida she was a high school dropout with 
three young children peter lived next door when the man she had 
married at 16 walked out 
he was my hero that came along and loved me and my children 
she said in her soft southern lilt 
she married him in 1981 in the brooksville courthouse believing 
he was james harold cassidy the charade crumbled a year later when 
he was arrested for burglarizing a church and a lumberyard police 
said he was peter gilbert a man who lived half his life as a 
criminal 
i couldnt understand why he lied to me i left him she said 
peter told her he lied only to get away from his past he said he 
stole to pay for the birth of their newborn daughter kiya he wrote 
poems from jail to win her forgiveness 
now that kiya binds our love there is no yesterday 
just tomorrow just for us our love will show the way 
a few months later peter escaped from a holding cell by knocking 
out another man who was to go before a judge on a minor charge 
peter took his place pleaded guilty to the other mans infraction 
and walked free 
he fled to rhode island against the advice of family and 
friends debra quit her waitressing job in brooksville to join him 
after a oneyear separation 
i was raising four kids and they missed him she said he 
said i was his life and after calling me all the time i believed 
him 
in rhode island she wondered why his beeper supposedly for his 
job at an auto body shop went off at all hours with strange 
messages she asked enough to learn he was involved with drugs 
but didnt pry 
i didnt want to know to be honest said debra now 30 
peters drug use became so bad he asked her to wake him by 
injecting him with cocaine she refused but stayed at his side 
telling herself he just needed help 
when police stormed her providence home in early 1985 debra 
learned about the murders all involving drug users or traffickers 
i tried to imagine him doing something like that she said 
i couldnt no matter how hard i tried 
authorities offered peter an unusual deal in exchange for his 
testimony he would serve his 10year sentence in providence police 
custody then be relocated the dream of starting over helped keep 
debra with her husband so did peters tales of threats against the 
family and prosecutors pleas he was a more believable witness with 
his wife by his side 
she sent her three older children to her mother in florida and 
she and 2yearold kiya were allowed to join peter in the police 
station 
the three lived together in a cell for a few weeks while a former 
matrons quarters was converted into a threeroom airconditioned 
apartment it had a telephone television videocassette recorder 
and queensized water bed but it was adjacent to the womens cells 
and the noise and screaming were incessant 
it was definitely our home said debra but it was like 
jail too i think i always felt like i was breathing germs 
peter passed the time watching tv sharing a beer with his 
guards fishing with the mayors chauffeur he started an 
autobiography he was allowed out and sometimes stayed away 
overnight 
debra was immobilied by fear afraid to go out she spent more 
time in jail than peter she began to fear the food might be 
poisoned and made her daughter wait while she tasted some first the 
strain finally proved too much and she moved back to florida 
i couldnt take it anymore the women screaming the officers 
my daughter was not going to be raised in that kind of 
environment she said 
two years later in 1988 she went back to peter at a rural rhode 
island safe house prosecutors provided debra said she told police 
that peter was using cocaine and packaging drugs in the cellar but 
was told to keep quiet a departmental review supports her 
allegation 
it can reasonably be inferred that gilbert supplemented his 
state income with his profits from narcotics sales the review 
said 
she stayed just seven weeks two months later peter who had a 
history of heart trouble died of a heart attack following a fight 
at a connecticut gas station according to a medical examiners 
report 
debra continues to wrestle with her husbands lies peter told 
the children he lived in the police station because he was an 
undercover officer she hasnt yet found a way to tell them the 
truth 
but she is hopeful about the future she recently remarried and 
insists this time she is less naive 
i have started a new life with a very good man she said 
its just a good feeling 
</TEXT>
