<TEXT>
a proapartheid candidate has 
made a surprisingly strong showing in a special parliamentary 
election widely seen as a referendum on president fw de klerks 
reforms 
in wednesdays vote held to fill a vacant seat in parliament 
from a workingclass district in durban ruling party candidate piet 
matthee defeated francis hitchcock of the proapartheid conservative 
party 
but the margin of victory 5762 to 5215 was far smaller than 
in last septembers white election when the candidate of the ruling 
national party outpolled the conservative candidate 6149 to 2429 
the conservatives said their performance improved because a 
growing number of whites are upset with de klerks plans to 
dismantle apartheid and negotiate a new constitution with black 
opposition groups 
de klerk has launched a series of reforms since assuming power in 
august he says he wants the countrys 5 million whites to share 
power with the 28 million blacks who currently have no voice in 
national affairs 
the conservatives oppose all concessions to blacks and want south 
africa divided into several separate states along racial lines 
they are the official opposition in the dominant white chamber of 
parliament with 39 seats the national party has 93 seats in the 
white chamber and the antiapartheid democratic party has 33 
the tricameral parliament also has houses for asians and people 
of mixedrace blacks vote only in local elections in segregated 
townships 
in septembers nationwide white elections the national party won 
48 percent the conservatives 31 percent and the democrats 21 
percent 
wednesdays election filled the seat vacated by the national 
partys con botha who has been named the administrator of natal 
province 
</TEXT>
