commerce secretary robert mosbacher signed an agreement wednesday 
with the soviet union that promises that federal officials will work 
with the soviets to find ways to adapt the us food making and 
distribution system to their country 
vladilen nikitin the soviet equivalent to the us agriculture 
secretary said the agreement was a small step but everything 
starts with a small step 
for you its a key if you want to participate in the 
strengthening of our economy he said through an interpreter 
the pact was signed on the last day of a threeday conference 
sponsored by the food processing machinery amp supplies association 
and the national food processors association 
mosbacher said the pact was unprecedented and a start toward 
expanding trade between the two superpowers 
we are the two largest industrialized nations in the world 
said mosbacher we have onethird of the worlds gnp gross 
national product but we do only a tiny fraction of world trade 
john cady president of the food processors association said 
barriers are beginning to come down although americans are 
concerned about getting paid for business with the soviets 
soviet currency is of almost no value in the world market 
leaving those companies doing business in the soviet union to either 
accept products in exchange or wait for longterm gains after the 
economy there improves 
we have to understand when companies invest its not going to 
be a threeyear turnaround but probably eight to 10 years said 
cady 
he said nikitin was a powerful official in the soviet government 
and would smooth the way for american business 
us businessmen at the conference had complained earlier of 
complications in dealing with the soviet bureaucracy 
</TEXT>
