<TEXT>
two major manufacturers of hair dryers have 
eliminated the danger of electrocution when their products fall into 
water says the consumer product safety commission 
the new hair dryers solve a problem which has plagued the 
industry since the early 1980s when an estimated 17 electrocutions 
annually were caused by handheld hair dryers falling into tubs and 
other water the commission said wednesday 
approximately 10 of these deaths were to children under 10 years 
of age the agency said 
youve got people that are drying their hair that have just 
come out of the shower whove got wet feet hands and hair said 
dick bruno vice president of marketing for windmere corp of miami 
the nations largest hair dryer manufacturer 
we wanted to take a position of providing the technology that 
was available he added 
windmeres new guardian esp hair dryers and curling iron and 
brush incorporate the new safety feature the classics protection 
plus hair dryer made by conair corp of stamford conn also 
includes the new safety feature 
the new dryers have rectangularshaped plugs with a reset button 
at the end of the cords 
a device called an appliance leakage current interrupter is built 
into the plug this detects any change in the electric current in 
the dryer within a fraction of a second and shuts the appliance off 
the new products offer protection against electrocution whether 
their switches are in the on or off position 
hair dryers manufactured since oct 1 1987 need only protect 
against electrocution if they fall into water with the switch in the 
off position the new dryers meet a new voluntary safety 
standard that becomes effective jan 1 1991 
</TEXT>
