<TEXT>
the state that started the nations tax revolt 
12 years ago is taking down the barricades californians have voted 
to double their gasoline tax and raise billions for mass transit 
schools and the poor 
fearful of ever growing traffic jams and eventual automotive 
gridlock california voters agreed to shoulder an average of 60 a 
year per motorist in new taxes and approved proposition 111 by a 
52to48 percent margin tuesday 
under the measure the state gas tax will go from 9 to 18 cents 
per gallon raising 155 billion for a 10year freeway building and 
improvement program 
in total dollars its the largest tax increase in california 
history 
the measure came more than a decade after californias 
proposition 13 started the national tax revolt conservatives in a 
dozen other states tried to copy california and at least half 
succeeded the tax revolt also was credited with helping establish 
the political climate that got ronald reagan elected in 1980 
the chief sponsor of proposition 111 conservative republican 
gov george deukmejian insists it was not an assault on the tax 
revolt movement because it was a specific tax for a specific purpose 
relief of traffic congestion 
there is no evidence in these results whatsoever to indicate 
that the public will now be supportive of a general tax increase 
where the revenues would go into the general fund for the purpose of 
expanding the size or scope of government he said wednesday 
if theres a lesson to be learned from this its that the 
public will support a specific increase in revenues provided they 
know exactly where that money is going to go i dont see any other 
lesson to be learned as a result of this vote on proposition 111 
but others see the california vote quite differently 
it really does end the tax revolt in california and sends a 
message to washington which i dislike intensely said conservative 
economist arthur laffer who helped win approval of the twin 
