<TEXT>
the police and some cabinet 
ministers have had wide restrictive powers under the 4yearold 
national state of emergency but many of the regulations have not 
uniformly been enforced since president fw de klerk came to power 
in august 
many of the powers granted to police under the emergency 
regulations already existed in security laws however the emergency 
decree bypassed the courts and granted police indemnity from 
prosecution for any action they took in good faith under the 
emergency 
here are some of the actions police and government ministers have 
taken under the national emergency declared by former president pw 
botha on june 12 1986 
more than 30000 people most of them black were detained for 
varying lengths of time without being charged with a crime some 
were held for nearly three years some were as young as 11 years old 
police did not have to tell inquiring relatives or lawyers 
whether they had a missing person in detention or give any 
information about a detainee to anyone 
newspapers were prohibited from reporting the names of detainees 
without police permission and it was illegal for anyone including 
freed detainees to describe the circumstances of detention 
when they were released the government could restrict former 
detainees to their homes prohibit them from working meeting with 
other people or participating in political activity although they 
had never been charged or convicted of a crime 
police without warrants could search any person building or 
vehicle and seize anything they wanted 
security officers could prohibit anyone from carrying out any 
activities or acts whatsoever 
more than 20 organizations were banned 
several newspapers were temporarily suspended from publication 
journalists were prohibited from being within sight of any 
political unrest and were immediately arrested if spotted by police 
tape recordings and film were seized without warrants 
journalists were prohibited from reporting about any police 
activity in connection with unrest unless police gave their 
permission local newspapers were prohibited from indicating whether 
news articles had been censored by the emergency regulations 
certain tshirts with slogans were made illegal police 
confiscated political banners flags and pamphlets under the 
emergency regulations even though they were not prohibited under any 
law passed by parliament 
all outdoor political rallies and demonstrations were banned at 
one time 
police issued regulations for funerals limiting the number of 
mourners designating who could speak setting the time and place 
for the burials 
the government banned subversive statements from being 
uttered or reported calls for boycotts strikes of foreign 
sanctions statements which might undermine the morale of the 
military and at one time any call for the release of detainees 
were defined as subversive 
