<TEXT>
thousands of people armed with spears stones and 
guns are massing along the border between the central asian 
republics of kirghizia and uzbekistan seeking to avenge the 48 
people who have died in ethnic warfare a top soviet official said 
today 
interior minister vadim bakatin told lawmakers in moscow that the 
violence which began three days ago in one town in kirghizia had 
spilled over to uzbekistan and spread to five regions in kirghizia 
a state of emergency was declared today in frunze the capital of 
kirghizia where one person died from a beating cars were destroyed 
and thousands of people surrounded communist party and government 
buildings an official said they demanded the resignation of the 
republics leaders and urged kirghiz to unite and strike back at 
uzbeks the tass news agency said kirghiz unite and kirghiz 
to osh they chanted referring to the frontier town 195 miles to 
the south where the fighting flared monday over a land dispute 
tass reported 
the unrest has been the latest in a series of ethnic outbreaks 
fueled by poverty or political conflict that have occurred in the 
more permissive political climate of president mikhail s 
gorbachevs 5year tenure 
the conflicts especially a bitter feud between armenia and 
azerbaijan in the caucusus have claimed hundreds of lives and 
forced tens of thousands of people to flee their homes in the face 
of attacks by rival ethnic groups 
an estimated 2000 uzbeks tried to cross the border from their 
republic to fight in osh but security forces stopped them and 
sealed all roads between uzbekistan and kirghizia the unofficial 
interfax news agency reported 
a state of emergency and curfew are in effect in osh with troops 
patrolling the streets and sealing off the city 
overnight in frunze security forces fired warning shots to 
disperse groups of students who committed acts of hooliganism 
damaging a childrens hospital a cloth factory and a market tass 
reported 
a state of emergency and curfew were declared in frunze where 
more than 4000 angry students rallied in the center of the city and 
demanded a chance to fight uzbeks said ivan v pavlov a department 
head on the citys party executive committee 
participants at the rally also gave leaders of the republic three 
days to resign tass said militia units held back the crowds 
a shopkeeper from the bazaar died today from a beating he 
received the day before said pavlov the city party official he 
said no further deaths were reported today but that angry crowds had 
destroyed 34 cars and several buses 
bakatin the top soviet law enforcement official told parliament 
that thousands of ethnic kirghiz and uzbeks were standing at the 
ready striving to avenge wrongdoings he said violence had been 
reported in uzbekistan and had spread to five regions in kirghizia 
but he did not identify the sites 
bakatin said the local clashes may develop into conflict 
between the two republics tass said 
the militia cannot handle interethnic conflicts particularly 
in the kindling of cavedwelling and medieval nationalism bakatin 
said in a speech to the soviet of nationalities one of two houses 
of the soviet parliament 
tasss englishlanguage service left out bakatins reference to 
cavedwelling and medieval which were carried on its russian 
wires 
the uzbeks and the kirghiz are predominantly sunni moslem ethnic 
groups that speak different turkic dialects 
soviet central asia with high levels of poverty and 
unemployment has been hit repeatedly by violence since gorbachev 
began to relax central controls the countrys worsening economic 
crisis has hit the region particularly hard 
in the fighting at osh since saturday 48 people have been 
killed 11 of them in the previous 24 hours and 333 injured 
including 42 law and order personnel 39 militiamen and three 
soldiers bakatin said 
security forces stood between the warring bands of kirghiz and 
uzbeks said bakatin adding that 1500 regular army soldiers 900 
interior ministry militia and troops and 450 troops under the kgb 
border guard were trying to keep order in osh 
the fighting was triggered by the distribution of land for 
individual houses in osh a heavily populated area along the 
twisting border between uzbekistan and kirghizia bakatin said 
he blamed the dispute on folly selfconceit and a bureaucratic 
approach to the division of land where the interests of one 
