<TEXT>
here is a list of the major 
political developments in south africa during the 4yearold state 
of emergency that was lifted in three of the countrys four 
provinces thursday 
june 12 1986 president pw botha imposes the emergency amid 
growing black unrest that has left hundreds dead thousands of 
activists are detained without trial within days the african 
national congress begins an urban bombing campaign 
july 1 1986 the government repeals the pass laws which 
required blacks to have an identity document and permission to be in 
white areas 
nov 5 1987 the government frees african national congress 
leader govan mbeki after 23 years in prison the government says his 
release is trial run for the freeing of other antiapartheid leaders 
such as nelson mandela one month later the government places tight 
restrictions on the 77yearold mbeki 
feb 24 1988 the government effectively bans 17 opposition 
groups including the united democratic front the largest legal 
antiapartheid organization at the time 
january 1989 some 1000 detainees go on a hunger strike 
demanding to be put on trial or released hundreds are released over 
a period of several weeks 
jan 18 1989 botha suffers a stroke he returns to work 
several weeks later but gives up his post as leader of the 
governing national party fw de klerk becomes party leader and 
heir apparent to botha 
july 5 1989 botha meets with mandela the jailed african 
national congress leader for a brief talk 
aug 14 1989 after disputes with his cabinet botha resigns 
de klerk assumes power 
sept 6 1989 de klerks national party wins white 
parliamentary elections some 20 blacks are killed in clashes with 
security forces the same day de klerk launches a series of reforms 
such as allowing peaceful demonstrations and opening segregated 
beaches to all races 
oct 15 1989 six african national congress leaders imprisoned 
for more than 25 years including walter sisulu are released two 
weeks later the first legal anc rally in 30 years draws 70000 
blacks in the soweto township outside johannesburg 
feb 2 1990 de klerk legalizes the anc and more than 60 
additional opposition groups suspends the death penalty eases 
emergency restrictions announces mandela will be released shortly 
feb 11 mandela is freed after more than 27 years in prison 
receives tumultuous welcomes in rallies in the countrys major 
cities 
may 24 the anc and the government hold their first talks they 
agree to work together to end violence and negotiate a new 
constitution that would end white domination and bring blacks into 
the national government 
june 7 president fw de klerk ends the national state of 
emergency but keeps emergency rules in effect in violencetorn 
natal province 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

