<TEXT>
acts of violence vandalism and harassment 
against gay people were widespread again last year but new 
antihatecrime laws offer hope the trend can be reversed according 
to a report released today 
the report was presented at a news conference by the national gay 
amp lesbian task force along with civil rights law enforcement and 
congressional leaders 
hate crimes exist because the narrowminded and meanspirited 
among us have judged some of their fellow citizens to be less 
deserving of respect than themselves said sen alan cranston 
dcalif the more that we bring these crimes to light the less 
tolerable they will be 
the fifth annual survey of antigay violence in the united 
states recounts 7031 such incidents in 1989 they ranged from 
verbal harassment to homicide and were documented by 119 
organizations and individuals in 40 states and the district of 
columbia 
last year the nations lesbian and gay community celebrated 
the 20th anniversary of the stonewall riots which sparked the 
modern gay rights movement said kevin berrill author of the 
report although we have made remarkable strides toward freedom 
since stonewall we remain a community under siege battling an 
epidemic of bigotry and violence 
in june 1968 patrons rioted at the stonewall a gay bar in new 
yorks greenwich village when police tried to raid it 
the data for the survey came from questionnaires sent to 650 gay 
activists and organizations nationwide the task force acknowledged 
its methods were unscientific and noted that more than half the 
groups that responded in 1988 did not do so in 1989 however the 
survey gives a broad look at the prevalence of antigay harassment 
and violence 
of the total incidents reported last year approximately 
twothirds were acts of verbal harassment the report said of the 
remaining 2322 incidents 34 percent were physical assaults 31 
percent were threats of violence 17 percent were acts of vandalism 
14 percent were police abuse 3 percent were homicides and 1 
percent were arson or other victimization 
nineteen percent occurred on college campuses revealing 
dangerous intolerance and prejudice that threatens an academic 
environment of enlightenment berrill said 
fifteen percent were classified by local groups as aidsrelated 
indicating that some people continue to use the disease as a 
justification for antigay prejudice and violence the report said 
but the report pointed to laws passed in 1989 and 1990 aimed at 
curbing bias crimes including those against gay people 
on april 23 1990 president bush signed the hate crimes 
statistics act which requires the federal government to collect 
data on crimes based on race religion sexual orientation and 
ethnicity the report called this an historic victory for the 
nations gay and lesbian community 
hate crimes laws with antigay provisions also recently passed 
in california connecticut the district of columbia iowa 
minnesota new hampshire oregon vermont atlanta burlington 
iowa montgomery county md and st louis according to the report 
for the most part states reporting the highest number of 
antigay incidents were those without hate crime laws that included 
homosexuals the report found 
states with the highest number of documented episodes were north 
carolina 1204 texas 997 california 563 illinois 529 and 
ohio 387 
overall 1989s total of 7031 episodes is slightly lower than 
the 7248 reported in 1988 the report noted 
it added however given the many factors that affect annual 
totals and the relatively minor difference between 1989 and 1988 
figures it is not possible to accurately gauge whether the problem 
increased or decreased last year 
