<DOCNO> AP900607-0073 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
without the national state of 
emergency the government still has wide powers under its security 
laws to restrict political activity 
by using the law and the courts government ministers and the 
police force can take most of the actions which the 4yearold 
emergency regulations allowed but there are some changes in the 
three provinces where president fw de klerk ordered the emergency 
ended 
people detained without trial or whose freedom of activity is 
restricted can challenge the action in court under the emergency 
judges discretion was generally limited to determining whether a 
particular action was covered by the emergency decree the decree 
said police were empowered to take any action and to tell anyone 
to do anything 
police no longer have automatic immunity from prosecution for 
actions they take in good faith in an unrest situation 
the power of the police to conduct warrantless searches and 
seizures is reduced but not eliminated 
police commissioners can no longer make sweeping bans on all 
rallies marches or public gatherings in their region they have to 
obtain a magistrates order to halt specific activities however 
the minister of law and order still has power under the law to 
declare any region an unrest area and impose emergency 
regulations within it 
police lose their power to place restrictions on funerals in 
black townships and to prohibit the display of certain slogans 
government ministers can no longer seize newspapers or suspend 
them at will they can still halt newspaper publication but must go 
through legal procedures and their action can be challenged in court 
police cannot order journalists or community workers away from 
an unrest area merely by invoking emergency regulations they 
can still issue such orders but must have a legal reason 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

