<TEXT>
the superpowers may complete a treaty on 30 
percent cuts in longrange nuclear weapons as early as november a 
senior us negotiator said today 
linton brooks deputy head of the us delegation to the geneva 
negotiations told reporters he was confident the treaty would be 
finished by the end of the year a target affirmed at last weeks 
summit by president bush and soviet president mikhail s gorbachev 
i think its possible to do it as early as sometime in 
november brooks said 
the three major areas of disagreement are on limits to soviet 
modernization of the ss18 ballistic missile constraints on the 
soviet backfire bomber and ways of limiting sales of longrange 
missiles to third countries 
brooks said the negotiators who return to the bargaining table 
in geneva on monday also have a lot of work left on details of an 
inspection regime for the treaty 
even as the superpowers are approaching the end of eight years of 
negotiations on this landmark treaty some critics are saying the 
ussoviet approach to reducing offensive nuclear weapons is 
becoming outdated 
on wednesday us and soviet scientists released a jointly 
published book that said future nuclear arms accords should provide 
for the destruction of warheads not just the missiles or other 
vehicles that deliver them 
the book reversing the arms race by the federation of 
american scientists and the committee of soviet scientists for 
global security also said the superpowers could cut the number of 
strategic nuclear weapons to less than 2000 on each side without 
creating an incentive to launch a preemptive first strike 
the ussoviet treaty nearing completion at the strategic arms 
reduction talks in geneva calls for a 30 percent reduction in 
strategic or longrange nuclear weapons to 6000 on each side 
the start treaty as drafted would not require the elimination of 
any warheads nor was there any such requirement in the 1987 
intermediaterange nuclear forces treaty that banned all us and 
soviet landbased missiles of medium range 
the start and inf treaties require destruction of missiles and 
missile launchers but put no restrictions on removing the 
fissionable material from the warheads and reusing it in other 
weapons not covered by the treaties 
allowing warheads from treatyprohibited weapons to be reused has 
not been a major drawback during an era in which both superpowers 
have tens of thousands of nuclear weapons the scientists said but 
it will become a problem in guarding against treaty cheating if 
future arms deals cut arsenals to minimal levels 
the scientist groups also said that for warhead dismantlement to 
be effective the superpowers should agree to halt production of new 
fissionable materials including plutonium tritium and enriched 
uranium used in warheads 
congress is increasingly interested in pursuing a ussoviet 
agreement to halt nuclear materials production but the bush 
administration is opposed 
the scientist groups noted that both moscow and washington 
already have had to reduce their nuclear materials production 
because of safety problems in manufacturing just this week new 
evidence emerged to indicate that problems at a key us weapons 
plant are more serious than previously believed 
</TEXT>
