habitats in national forest management agriculture secretary 
clayton yuetter said thursday 
yeutter and us forest service chief f dale robertson unveiled 
a longterm plan for forest and range land resources calling for 
greater environmental sensitivity and a better balance among 
multiple uses of public lands 
the secretary said production levels will be reduced in areas 
where timber and mineral production and livestock grazing cannot be 
accomplished in an environmentally acceptable manner 
we are looking at multipleuse management from a new 
perspective yeutter said during a news conference at the 
agriculture department 
this plan calls for some reductions in timber harvests and 
livestock range grazing in order to enhance and protect the 
ecological balances there he said 
president bush in a formal statement to congress called the 
blueprint an ambitious program that strongly renews my 
commitment to multipleuse management 
the plan which the agriculture department is required to present 
to congress every five years under the resources planning act of 
1974 was hailed by at least one environmental group for placing 
greater emphasis on fishing and wildlife habitats 
in the past they had a telescope on trees period much of the 
emphasis has been on timber and forest products trout unlimited 
executive director robert l herbst said 
leaders of the timber industry condemned the report during a 
tuesday news conference saying the projections are worthless 
because they ignore such critical factors as the anticipated listing 
of the rare northern spotted owl as a threatened species 
the us fish and wildlife service is to decide by june 23 
whether to declare the owl as threatened a move congressmen in the 
pacific northwest say would result logging bans across large 
sections of the region 
yeutter acknowledged the industrys concern that the rpa proposal 
will have to be altered to take the owl into consideration if it is 
listed under the endangered species act but he said that will not 
be done until a formal announcement is made on the owls status 
were not going to do an rpa on the basis of hypotheticals 
he said 
robertson added that timberbased communities should understand 
also that the owl listing could carry significant impacts not 
accounted for in the rpa report 
theres no question were going to have to provide more 
protection for the spotted owl even if its not listed 
robertson said 
timber harvests on national forest lands which averaged 122 
billion board feet from 198388 will fall to about 108 billion 
board feet by 1995 then begin to grow slowly again to about 12 
billion board feet by 2040 the report said 
