<TEXT>
president fw de klerk today 
lifted the 4yearold state of emergency in most of the country and 
challenged black nationalist leaders to respond to his governments 
reforms 
de klerks decision to end repressive emergency measures removes 
a major obstacle to negotiations with the african national congress 
on ending apartheid and giving the black majority a voice in the 
government 
i have decided to announce there will no longer be a general 
countrywide state of emergency but that henceforth it will exist in 
natal province only de klerk said in a speech to parliament 
black factional fighting in the southeastern province of natal 
has left about 500 people dead since the first of the year 
the president also announced that as a goodwill gesture he was 
releasing 48 prisoners convicted of politically motivated crimes 
members of the proapartheid conservative party burst into 
laughter when de klerk began his speech to parliament by saying he 
had received a mandate from white voters for reform 
we are on the threshold of the real negotiation process and the 
time has come for other important role players to do their bit de 
klerk said in particular the anc must now stop vacillating 
many of the emergency regulations are duplicated in existing 
legislation however without the regulations police will no longer 
have immunity from prosecution for any action they take in an unrest 
situation police commissioners lose their power to impose sweeping 
bans on public gatherings they will have to prove the necessity of 
each restriction in court 
police will lose their control over funerals in black townships 
government will not be able to suspend or seize newspapers at will 
police once again will need warrants for most searches and seizures 
the african national congress has said the lifting of the 
emergency the release of prisoners and the return of exiles are the 
main obstacles to full negotiation on a new constitution 
the white house called the lifting of the state of emergency in 
most of south africa a sign of the remarkable progress 
we look forward to the early beginning of a negotiating 
process deputy white house press secretary alixe glen told 
reporters flying aboard air force one with president bush to a 
speaking engagement in milwaukee this is another significant step 
toward creating a climate conducive to negotiations that will lead 
to a democratic nonracial south africa 
de klerk said his government has accepted a joint program on 
those major issues worked out last month by midlevel officials on 
both sides he said he is ready to implement it but the anc has 
said it will not have a response until july 10 
de klerk says he wants the new constitution to allow the 
countrys 28 million blacks to share power with the 5 million whites 
the president today reiterated his call for an end to 
international sanctions against his government 
in paris anc leader nelson mandela called de klerks move a 
victory for the people but he urged the west to maintain the 
economic sanctions 
some south african newspapers have said that by ending the 
emergency now de klerk could be trying to undermine mandela as he 
tours the world calling for continued sanctions 
the emergency laws which included some of the harshest 
restrictions on political activity ever imposed by south africas 
white rulers had to be renewed by midnight friday if they were to 
remain in effect for another year 
more than 30000 activists almost all of them black have been 
detained without trial for varying lengths of time during the 
emergency others went into hiding about 300 remain in detention 
now 
most of the countrys leading newspapers had predicted de klerk 
would lift the decree during his speech to lawmakers a sixhour 
cabinet meeting was held wednesday at which the emergency was 
discussed at length 
de klerks predecessor pw botha declared the nationwide 
emergency on june 12 1986 in a bid to quell mounting black unrest 
de klerk had nullified some of the emergency restrictions as part 
of a series of reforms implemented since he assumed power in august 
he also has released scores of detainees and longterm political 
prisoners 
but de klerk said today the violence in natal province cannot 
be countered with the ordinary laws of the land 
the anc has acknowledged that the violence there is worse than in 
other parts of the country while he has not called for a continued 
state of emergency there mandela has suggested that the government 
use the full force of its military and police to stop the killing 
the main combatants in natal are supporters of the african 
national congress and members of the conservative zulu organization 
inkatha 
an estimated 6000 blacks have died in the past four years 4000 
of them in blackonblack violence in natal but scores have been 
killed in clashes with police including more than 30 deaths in 
recent months 
mandela on a sixweek trip to europe north america and africa 
conferred with french officials today 
the lifting of the emergency decree is what we have fought for 
since the emergency was declared in june 1986 mandela told 
journalists but it doesnt change my mind regarding the need 
for sanctions 
in pressuring for an end to apartheid the united states and 
other countries have restricted trade with and investment in south 
africa 
mandela was freed in february after more than 27 years in south 
african prisons he and de klerk have held preliminary negotiations 
aimed at clearing away obstacles for formal talks 
in his speech today de klerk again challenged mandela to stop 
advocating continued guerrilla activity de klerk criticized 
mandelas statement in botswana earlier this week that the anc 
approves of organized disciplined violence against chosen 
targets 
on two other major issues de klerk held out the prospect of 
reforms soon he said the government is considering changing 
security legislation that could possibly inhibit the free conduct 
of peaceful politics 
he also said the government has started to act on allowing 
thousands of exiles to return home the anc says it has more than 
15000 exiled members 
anticipating de klerks announcement conservative spokesman 
moolman metnz said beforehand that lifting the emergency would cause 
chaos they couldnt cope with the violence even with the state of 
emergency because they were not applying it our view is the 
government is trying to appease everybody 
 
