<TEXT>
displaced homemakers often face poverty and 
limited job opportunities a private group said thursday 
if you choose homemaking youre choosing a very highrisk 
occupation said jill miller executive director of the national 
displaced homemakers network 
women forced to seek jobs outside the home after spending years 
as fulltime homemakers often lack training and have to take 
parttime seasonal jobs miller said 
the number of displaced homemakers rose 12 percent over the past 
decade from 139 million in 1980 to 156 million in 1989 according 
to a report by the washingtonbased group based on census bureau 
figures 
displaced homemakers are women whose main job was homemaking but 
who lost their key source of income through widowhood divorce 
separation or because a spouse suffered disability or longterm 
unemployment 
we are penalizing homemakers and leaving them high and dry 
when they make that choice she said noting that other workers 
are eligible for unemployment benefits 
nearly three in five displaced homemakers were living near or 
below the poverty level the report said about one in five or 3 
million american women are living in households with other 
families it said 
the group said there were 22 million american married women in 
1989 who were fulltime homemakers 
