<TEXT>
the soviet union and united states may agree 
this year on an experimental program for increasing each sides 
observation of the others antimissile defense work a senior us 
negotiator said thursday 
david smith chief us delegate to the geneva negotiations on 
defense and space told reporters such an accord was possible as 
early as this year but he saw little likelihood of completing a 
formal treaty on the use of spacebased defenses against strategic 
ballistic missiles within the next two years 
he said there was no official target date for completing the 
defense and space treaty which in the us view would govern a 
gradual transition by both countries from offensive to defensive 
means of deterring nuclear war but the soviets dont accept that 
concept saying it would lead to a new more expensive more 
dangerous and unpredictable arms race in space 
smith said the experimental program as proposed by the united 
states would be an important sign of progress in the geneva talks 
which have been bogged down lately 
the united states has proposed an executive agreement on 
predictability measures designed to build confidence in both 
washington and moscow that neither side is trying to conceal its 
intentions in researching spacebased dcist running hard in arkansas and 
a charismatic exklan 
leader seeking to represent louisiana in the us senate 
while mainstream candidates denounce the extremist views some 
civil rights officials voice concern 
they see a fearful trend in the candidacies of jb stoner and 
ralph forbes who seek nominations for lieutenant governor in 
georgia and arkansas and are especially troubled by david dukes 
run for the senate in louisiana 
this is part of a new strategy that the white supremacists have 
developed to work within the electoral system while at the same 
time building their underground operation says eva sears of the 
center for democratic renewal an atlantabased organization that 
monitors the ku klux klan and similar groups 
the klan has elected members to congress and to many state 
offices in the past but those who watch white supremacists say 
their strategies have evolved and the stakes have gone up 
whats new is the extent of the support that theyre getting 
says irwin suall of the antidefamation league of bnai brith in 
new york 
financial support votes suall continues the amount seems 
to be sufficient to take them out of the category of fringe 
candidate 
duke who left the klan to lead the national association for the 
advancement of white people has reported receiving nearly 600000 
in donations to his campaign for the gop nomination for the seat now 
held by sen bennett johnston duke insists hes now merely a 
champion of whites civil rights not a white supremacist 
forbes a former american nazi leader won 46 percent of the vote 
in last months primary for the gop nomination for arkansas 
lieutenant governor a runoff is set for tuesday 
the numbers that ralph forbes polled will be used time and 
time and time again to show that people do sympathize with the views 
of white supremacists says pat clark who heads klanwatch a 
monitoring group in montgomery ala 
the balloting figures will become a recruiting tool she 
says its not necessary always to have a definite victory in the 
sense of being elected 
indeed victory often has been elusive since the klans electoral 
successes of the 1920s when as university of florida history 
professor david chalmers puts it the ku klux klan elected 
senators and governors literally from maine to california 
even president warren harding agreed to be sworn in as a kkk 
member in a white house ceremony according to another scholar wyn 
craig wade in his klan history the fiery cross 
but at that time the klan was at its height with an estimated 5 
million members now monitoring groups say there are perhaps 5000 
kkk members and 17000 or so americans who belong to other racist 
organizations 
thats part of the reason why some thought dukes 1989 victory on 
his third try for a seat in the louisiana legislature was 
significant 
it propelled people to think ok now weve seen it be 
successful lets try it once more weve definitely seen more 
people jump on the bandwagon says ms clark 
it was the first time theyve been able to successfully elect 
people to office since the demise of jim crow in the 1960s says 
leonard zeskind research director of the center for democratic 
renewal 
these guys ran for office before but they never had this 
kind of strategy of being a hardcore white supremacist and passing 
yourself off as a righttolifer or antiaffirmative action 
duke in a telephone inteview from baton rouge says hes been 
misunderstood and maligned but he agrees with civil rights 
officials that a victory in the us senate race oct 6 would 
reverberate far beyond louisiana 
i think a senate victory would send a message to elected 
officials across america that theyve got to start listening to the 
majority duke sayswhen im elected with my admittedly 
controversial background its going to make it easier for other 
people to begin to talk about the issues that im speaking about 
asked about photos of himself in nazi garb duke dismisses them 
as part of a college stunt when he picketed a leftwing campus 
speaker 
asked about statements attributed to him in his own naawp news 
such as the media is dominated by jews not good americans 
and north americans and europeans are like islands of light in a 
hungry and backward third world sea duke says now i believe 
in freedom i dont believe in forced integration and i also 
dont believe in forced segregation i believe in less 
government 
asked about his leadership of a klan group he notes that was 12 
years ago 
i think i have a right to change and develop just like anybody 
else he says 
he adds that many of his views differ from those of forbes who 
was once his campaign manager and of stoner 
forbes running against a black candidate in the runoff recently 
reiterated his belief that racial separation is ultimately the 
right answer 
a minister forbes cites the bible in support of his views 
his runoff opponent kenneth muskie harris speculates that 
forbes might have placed first in the primary because although he 
wasnt wellknown he had better name recognition than his two 
opponents and his name was listed first on the ballot his former 
membership in the nazi party also was not widely known among voters 
as for stoner who served a prison term for bombing a black 
church in alabama in 1958 his antiblack and antisemitic campaign 
rhetoric has prompted some fellow democratic candidates to threaten 
to boycott joint appearances 
analysts give stoner no chance of winning in the july 17 primary 
but say racist candidates may tap into a backlash among some white 
voters 
wayne parent a professor of political science at louisiana state 
university who has followed dukes career says he and other 
candidates represent the remnants of george wallaceism and hope 
to take advantage of voter resentment of changes in society brought 
on by the civil rights movement 
duke has been denied official republican sanction but as far 
as making those republicans turn to the right he seems to have had 
some success parent says because his message is selling better 
than people thought 
jane hardisty director of the cambridge massbased political 
research associates which studies the political right wing says 
white supremacists have devoted themselves to politics more 
seriously since a series of arrests in the 1980s effectively set 
back the violent approach as the medium for the message 
voiced by politicians who carry no guns and wear no robes the 
message still has a waiting audience she says 
if youre in a position where your standard of living is 
falling you have job insecurity that you didnt use to have youre 
looking for an explanation for that ms hardisty says 
and theyre providing a fairly simple easy scapegoat blame 
it on some specific group the jews or the blacks whoever 
resentment among the electorate and the increasing sophistication 
of white supremacist candidates make a formidable combination that 
is hard to disentangle says ms sears of the center for democratic 
renewal 
if you had a big fire how much of it was the dry wood and how 
much was the gasoline 
