<TEXT>
lower back pain is better remedied by a good 
stretch than expensive electronic gadgetry according to a study 
published thursday 
the results of the study indicate that widely used transcutaneous 
electrical nerve stimulation or tens appears to be no more 
effective than a placebo said dr richard a deyo lead author of 
the study published in the new england journal of medicine 
it appeared to do nothing in our study it was a resounding 
negative result the university of washington researcher told 
reporters wednesday 
a major manufacturer of the devices empi corp of st paul 
minn criticized the study saying the 30day length was not long 
enough 
other studies done over a longer time frame have reinforced our 
belief that tens devices are an effective lowcost alternative to 
narcotic drug therapy and surgery for many pain sufferers donald 
maurer empi chairman said 
tens units about the size of a personal cassette player are 
carried on the belt they include wires with electrodes placed on 
the skin in the area of pain deyo said they cost about 500 and 
have been used for about 20 years 
he said use of tens resulted from the belief that 
counterstimulation of the nervous system could modify perception of 
pain like rubbing a bump on the head 
it was later believed that tens lowfrequency highamplitude 
electrical stimulation could raise the level of opiatelike 
substances endorphins in the spinal fluid 
but little clinical evidence existed on the machines 
effectiveness the researchers who also included doctors at the 
university of texas health science center at san antonio ran 
clinical tests using 145 patients with chronic back pain from 1985 
to 1987 in san antonio 
they were broken into four groups tens plus exercise tens 
alone exercise with sham tens and sham tens alone 
all four groups reported significant improvement after two and 
four weeks of participation but had relapsed by the twomonth 
followup 
there were no clinically important or statistically significant 
differences in any outcome between the subjects receiving true tens 
and those receiving sham tens the study concluded 
by contrast the analysis of the effects of exercise showed an 
advantage of exercise in several outcomes including reduction in 
reported frequency of pain 
deyos advice try exercise first and be persistent he said 
those working at exercise to help chronic back pain should expect no 
quick fixes but should see improvements over time 
he also advised against surgery for muscleoriented pain and 
against powerful medications 
he said tens may be effective for acute pain or pain in other 
parts of the body but he said he hoped the research would prompt 
others to study the tens effectiveness 
the study said americans spend 13 billion each year on lower 
back pain treatments athough no estimate of national expenditures 
for tens is available deyo said the veterans administration in 1986 
spent 2 million to purchase them 
deyo is director of health services research and development at 
the seattle veterans affairs medical center as well as a university 
of washington associate professor of medicine and health services 
he said he expected a public relationstype assault against 
the study adding that a halfdozen manufacturers of tens devices do 
business in the united states 
others involved in the study included dr nicholas walsh 
chairman of the department of physical medicine rehabilitation at 
the university of texas dr donald martin at the university of 
washington and drs lawrence schoenfeld and somayaji ramamurthy at 
the university of texas 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

