<TEXT>
president fw de klerks 
lifting of the national state of emergency was welcomed thursday by 
world leaders but drew some domestic criticism for going too far 
or not far enough 
the african national congress the black nationalist group that 
has spearheaded the antiapartheid movement called the government 
actions half measures 
rightwing whites on the other hand intensified their 
criticisms of de klerk 
un secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar called de klerks 
move a positive development and the white house hailed the move 
as a sign of the remarkable progress being made in south africa 
de klerk lifted the 4yearold emergency in most of the country 
but retained the rules in violencetorn natal province and the zulu 
homeland 
anc leader walter sisulu said the state of emergency had done 
nothing to stop the fighting in natal sisulu told a news conference 
that if de klerk wants to create the right climate for negotiations 
on ending apartheid the emergency should be lifted in the troubled 
eastern province as well 
we are not asking for half measures sisulu said what we 
have asked for is to clear the atmosphere to negotiations that was 
not done 
sisulu said natal violence could be eased with the lifting of the 
state of emergency and by the government taking positive steps to 
prevent police brutality in the area 
in paris anc leader nelson mandela also criticized the decision 
to retain the state of emergency in natal he also said it was still 
too early to end international sanctions against south africa 
still he called the lifting of the state of emergency a 
victory for the people both black and white 
about 4000 blacks have died in violence in natal during the past 
four years the main combatants are supporters of the anc and 
members of inkatha a relatively conservative zulu organization 
inkatha leader mangosuthu buthelezi who heads the zulu homeland 
government said it was lamentably tragic that the emergency 
remained in force in natal 
i find it politically altogether unacceptable that i who 
was among the first to declare his readiness to negotiate now finds 
himself locked into an emergencyridden region buthelezi said 
the anc also wants the government to repeal security laws that 
still allow detention without trial even though the emergency decree 
has been lifted 
anyone of us in this room can be detained now said anc 
official mohammed valli moosa who was detained three times during 
the emergency the de facto situation on the ground in the 
townships doesnt really change 
meanwhile the proapartheid conservative party said the end of 
the emergency would lead to chaos elsewhere in the country 
they the government couldnt cope with the violence even with 
the state of emergency because they were not applying it said 
moolman mentz a spokesman for the conservatives our view is the 
government is trying to appease everybody 
the south african chamber of business praised de klerks action 
calling it an important step toward national reconciliation it 
said stability was essential for business and investment in south 
africa 
de klerk wants to work out a new constitution with opposition 
groups that will lead to powersharing between the 5 million whites 
and 28 million blacks who currently have no voice in national 
affairs 
