north carolina led the nation in acts of 
violence vandalism and harassment against homosexuals in 1989 a 
year during which such episodes were prevalent nationwide according 
to a survey of gay organizations 
a total of 7031 incidents of antigay violence or harassment 
occurred last year in 40 states and the district of columbia 
according to the report antigay violence victimization amp 
defamation in 1989 of those 1204 took place in north carolina 
the survey found 
these attacks occurred in a context of widespread violence 
against jews people of color and women said kevin berrill the 
reports author and director of the antiviolence project at the 
national gay amp lesbian task force 
he cited the death of yusuf hawkins a black youth killed by 
whites in brooklyn ny the firebombing of the san diego jewish 
times the beating death of an asian in raleigh nc and racist 
bombings in birmingham ala and savannah ga that killed a 
federal judge and a civil rights lawyer 
hate crimes exist because the narrowminded and meanspirited 
among us have judged some of their fellow citizens to be less 
deserving of respect than themselves sen alan cranston 
dcalif said at a news conference to release the report the 
more that we bring these crimes to light the less tolerable they 
will be 
berrill said antigay violence remains largely hidden he said 
gay people should report such crimes he also called on more states 
to pass hate crimes laws similar to the federal hate crimes 
statistics act signed in april by president bush 
the report said hate crime laws with antigay provisions recently 
passed in california connecticut the district of columbia iowa 
minnesota new hampshire oregon and vermont they also were adopted 
in atlanta burlington iowa montgomery county md and st louis 
the report said 
