<TEXT>
federal investigators who found 15000 
violations of child labor laws during a threeday nationwide sweep 
in march followed with a surprise oneday effort this week the 
labor department said thursday 
the nearly 1000 enforcement officials who fanned out across the 
country wednesday did not immediately report the number of 
violations they uncovered at nearly 1900 businesses the department 
said 
during the march sweep agents visited mostly fastfood 
restaurants grocery stores and other service businesses that employ 
large numbers of youngsters 
this weeks effort was broadened to include agriculture workers 
and the garment industry officials said 
were trying to see if the problem is pervasive or if it is 
just in the metropolitan areas said johanna schneider a labor 
department spokesman 
the majority of the alleged violations uncovered in march 
involved firms in which 14 and 15yearolds worked more hours or 
later at night during the school week than allowed under federal law 
but there were also hundreds of youngsters mostly 16 and 
17yearolds who were performing dangerous tasks or using hazardous 
equipment such as powerdriven meatslicing machinery dough mixers 
and paperbalers 
of the 3900 businesses visited in march nearly half were in 
apparent violation of child labor laws officials said 
after the march blitz investigators first reported 7000 
violations but the total rose to 15500 after further reviews of 
payroll records the labor department said 
fines stemming from the march sweep are expected to total 5 
million up from the original estimate of 18 million in fines the 
agency said 
last year the labor departments wage and hour division which 
enforces child labor provisions of the fair labor standards act 
found 22508 minors to be illegally employed an alltime high 
fines totaling 27 million were assessed during all of 1989 
on friday a house panel will continue hearings into child labor 
violations those scheduled to testify include parents of youngsters 
killed on the job officials from burger king mcdonalds and 
dominos pizza are also scheduled to appear 
federal law forbids 14 and 15yearolds from working more than 
three hours on a school day or 18 hours in a week during the school 
year eight hours is permitted on weekend days and 40hour weeks are 
permitted in summer and during vacations 
youngsters under 14 are prohibited from working in all but a few 
exempt jobs such as newspaper delivery workers 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

