<TEXT>
a senate panel voted thursday to slash an 
administration request for additional money to tear down and rebuild 
the new us embassy in moscow which is riddled with electronic 
listening devices 
the senate foreign relations committee voted 150 for an 
amendment offered by sen daniel patrick moynihan dny to cut 
the 270 million figure the state department had asked for the 
coming year to 50 million 
the vote was largely symbolic because it came on legislation that 
is unlikely to be enacted into law 
however it illustrated the continuing controversy over what to 
do with the eightstory structure suffused with soviet listening 
technology on which the government already has spent 60 million 
both democrats and republicans on the panel arguing in support 
of moynihans move said it would be a waste to tear down an nearly 
completed building that could be used for other purposes for which 
soviet eavesdropping would not be a problem 
moynihan argued that the 50 million he left in the bill would be 
enough to complete the compromised chancery building and construct a 
smaller building elsewhere in the embassy compound to house 
sensitive intelligence and other secret operations 
that idea is vigorously opposed by the state department which 
wants to tear the chancery down to its foundation and rebuild it for 
its originally planned use as the primary office building for the 
complex 
intelligence experts including the senate intelligence 
committee have endorsed that approach as the only secure one 
the house foreign affairs committee in a separate version of the 
legislation has included the full 270 million but left open the 
question of whether it would be spent on a new building or 
reconstructing the present one 
the skirmish over the embassy building came on a measure sought 
by the administration that also would authorize spending 474 
million to pay pastdue dues to the united nations 
sen jesse helms rnc signaled that if the measure comes to 
the senate floor he would seek to delete that money from the bill 
in addition the measure included a series of addons most from 
democrats to address pet concerns the provisions included 74 
million sought by moynihan to control sea lampreys and zebra mussels 
in the great lakes 
</TEXT>
