<TEXT>
leaders of a house committee introduced a 
bipartisan bill thursday to pay for improvements in the nations air 
travel system without tax increases or fees proposed by the bush 
administration 
the plan by the democratic and republican leadership of the house 
public works and transportation committee calls for spending 177 
billion over the next two fiscal years which is close to what 
president bush has requested 
but a large share of the money would come from the aviation trust 
fund which has accumulated 76 billion from passenger fees and 
other tax revenue bush wants new airport passenger fees and 
increased federal ticket taxes and taxes on aviation fuel 
the house aviation subcommittee is scheduled to take up the bill 
june 14 
we are proposing to authorize this funding that will benefit 
all airline passengers without a federal tax increase said rep 
glenn m anderson dcalif committee chairman 
other bill sponsors include the committees ranking republican 
rep paul hammerschmidt of arkansas along with the chairman and 
ranking minority member of the aviation subcommittee reps james l 
oberstar dminn and william f clinger jr rpa 
oberstar said the measure would reduce money in the trust fund to 
12 billion by fiscal 1995 
we see no ned for a federal tax increase for aviation while we 
have a 76 billion surplus in the trust fund oberstar said 
he said the committees plan envisions expansion of the nations 
aviation capacity through airport development modernization of 
the air traffic control system and improved system operations 
the bill would authorize 18 billion in fiscal 1991 and 19 
billion in fiscal 1992 for the airport improvement program and 25 
billion in 1991 and 3 billion in 1992 for aviation facilities and 
equipment it also would authorize 41 billion for operation in 
1991 about half of which would come from the trust fund in fiscal 
1992 that would increase to 44 billion 
the bill would eliminate penalty clauses applying to the trust 
fund that are designed to ensure that the greater share of the fund 
be spent for capital improvements rather than operation of the 
federal aviation administration the clauses limit the proportion of 
funding that can go to operations 
</TEXT>
