<TEXT>
a group of us healthcare companies have 
joined soviet officials to create a program that will share 
technology and research to improve care for children in both 
countries 
officials of childrens health system inc based in norfolk 
va said thursday the agreement with the soviet ministry of health 
would help meet that countrys needs for medical supplies drugs 
technology and advanced training 
the agreement was signed last month in moscow where two eastern 
virginia medical school pediatricians who represented childrens 
health system toured moscows leading pediatric hospitals 
drs raymond d adelman and rebecca l byrd said the soviet 
facilities were 10 to 15 years out of date and in urgent need of 
medical supplies equipment and drugs 
us physicians adelman said will benefit by learning about 
some of the new techniques and procedures the soviets have perfected 
about 90 percent of the patients in soviet pediatric hospitals 
would be treated as outpatients in the us health care system 
however because of a shortage of medical specialists and 
services in many areas of the soviet union children must travel 
hundreds of miles for appropriate care 
one public health problem facing the soviets is that many 
families refuse to have their children immunized because of the 
possibility they will contract aids byrd said 
unlike the united states where disposable syringes are used 
soviet physicians use reusable syringes which if not sterilized can 
transmit bloodborne diseases she said 
the exchange to be funded with donations from corporations and 
foundations will begin in september and will start with a few 
physicians and other health care professionals in each country 
adelman said 
he said the soviet health care system cannot improve dramatically 
without adequate supplies of medical equipment and improvement in 
basic technology 
the exchange program called the usussr childrens health 
center will work with soviet authorities to facilitate the sale of 
american medical supplies drugs and technologies he said 
the childrens health system network is anchored by childrens 
hospital of the kings daughters a nonprofit specialized 
pediatric hospital in norfolk 
</TEXT>
