<TEXT>
romania must spend more than 25 
million for emergency repairs from last weeks earthquake that 
killed 14 people and injured about 1000 across central and eastern 
europe an official said thursday 
the government also appealed for foreign help in making this 
earthquakeprone country better equipped to handle temblors 
mihai grigoriu a top official in the economy ministry said last 
weeks quake carved a trail of damage through 14 of romanias 40 
counties including the capital city of bucharest 
grigoriu said experts started examining the damaged buildings in 
romania and noticed most older structures that were damaged in major 
quakes in 1977 and 1986 were also battered by the latest temblor 
the earthquake and its aftershocks may 3031 did major damage at 
400 schools 200 hospitals as well as many city halls in bucharest 
and other communities across this balkan nation of 23 million 
people grigoriu said 
the uppsala seismological center in sweden said the quake was 
centered about 63 miles under the earth causing tremors to be felt 
in bulgaria soviet moldavia yugoslavia and turkey it registered 
up to 68 on the richter scale 
apart from damage to buildings romanias 25 million loss also 
includes export goods such as tons of wood glass and tiles 
grigoriu told the associated press 
we could have well exported these materials to the west or to 
asia for hard currency he said 
officials have given no estimate for costs other than urgently 
needed repairs 
although no buildings collapsed chunks of concrete fell from 
highrise buildings on virtually every street in the capital 
in the city above the earthquakes epicenter focsani about 190 
miles northeast of bucharest 500 apartments were damaged and 
people were evacuated from four blocks of apartment buildings 
grigoriu said 
eugen ionescu a spokesman for the ministry of foreign affairs 
told a news conference thursday the romanian government would accept 
offers from other governments or international groups on improving 
its ability to handle earthquakes 
romania has a long history of damaging earthquakes with three or 
four major quakes a century according to official statistics more 
than 1500 romanians died in the 1977 quake 
the government has asked local groups in romania to make up a 
list of preworld war ii buildings at high risk of collapsing in the 
next major quake 
officials will then decide on the demolition of those buildings 
that are not worth any more money invested or are not worth being 
repaired grigoriu said 
</TEXT>
