us officials and political activists praised 
the end of the state of emergency in south africa on thursday but 
said the action doesnt warrant the removal of us sanctions 
the white house said the move by south african president fw de 
klerk was a sign of the remarkable progress made by the 
whiteminority government 
de klerk ended a 4yearold national state of emergency in all 
but the nations natal province the policy imposed some of the 
governments harshest political restrictions on the countrys 
blackmajority population 
this is another significant step toward creating a climate 
conducive to negotiations that will lead to a democratic nonracial 
south africa said deputy white house press secretary alixe glen 
it is a long overdue and important step which will help pave 
the way to end the brutal system of apartheid said sen edward 
kennedy dmass the prime sponsor of the 1986 antiapartheid act 
the legislation barred landing rights in the united states to 
south african airways banned us import of south african uranium 
and coal and prohibited new us investments and bank loans in the 
racially segregated country 
apartheid is still in place kennedy said adding this is 
no time for the united states or any other nation to lift any 
sanctions 
its an important step forward but it clearly does not meet the 
requirements of the lifting of sanctions echoed rep ronald 
dellums dcalif chairman of the congressional black caucus 
at the state department deputy spokesman richard boucher noted 
that the bush administration cannot legally modify us sanctions 
against south africa until certain conditions are met 
the law says the restrictions would be lifted automatically if 
president bush reported to congress that the south african 
government satisfied specific conditions for ending them 
the law requires the south african government to repeal the state 
of emergency nationwide and free black nationalist leader nelson 
mandela as it did last february additionally the government must 
release all other political prisoners legalize opposition political 
parties and their activities and enter into goodfaith negotiation 
with representative black leaders without preconditions 
the south african government also must repeal the group areas act 
and the population registration act which restrict the movement and 
residence of nonwhites to comply us preconditions 
randall robinson executive director of transafrica a group that 
lobbies on concerns of africa and the caribbean commended the 
action but called it a tiny measure 
it is a little late and all too small considering the distance 
that must be traveled in a very short space of time he added 
