<TEXT>
an alzheimers disease diagnosis is absolute only 
after an autopsy experts said thursday in the wake of the 
doctorassisted suicide of a woman who had been told she had the 
incurable illness 
the difficulty in some cases is that it may be misdiagnosed 
said michelle manning deputy director of the alzheimers 
associations detroitarea chapter 
as many as 80 diseases can appear to be alzheimers which 
affects up to 4 million people most of them elderly manning said 
alzheimers is a degenerative brain and nerve disorder that robs 
people of their memories abilities to function and eventually their 
lives 
a new spotlight has focused on alzheimers since monday when dr 
jack kevorkian of suburban royal oak hooked janet adkins 54 to a 
machine and watched her die as she pressed a button that pumped 
heartstopping chemicals into her system 
kevorkian had driven with mrs adkins of portland ore to a 
park outside detroit and attached her to the electricpowered device 
in the back of his van kevorkian said she was dead within minutes 
after she pressed the button 
mrs adkins who had despaired after being told a year ago she 
had alzheimers had read of kevorkians device and thought that 
sounded like a very very humane and painless way to end her life 
said her husband ronald 
michigan state police seized kevorkians van and suicide device 
after he reported mrs adkins death monday prosecutors planned to 
seek an injunction to stop kevorkian from using the device again at 
a friday hearing in oakland county circuit court 
the medical examiners office refused to release results of mrs 
adkins autopsy thursday the prosecutors office did not return 
several calls ronald adkins said thursday that the autopsy which 
his wife had requested had not been completed 
medical experts said extensive tests must be conducted when a 
person is suspected of having alzheimers but the diagnosis isnt 
definite until brain tissue is examined under a microscope they 
said 
its always called probable alzheimers disease thats 
probable in capital letters said dr creighton phelps vice 
president of medical and scientific affairs for the chicagobased 
alzheimers association 
the criteria fordefinite diagnosis is after death he said 
a probable diagnosis is usually between 80 percent and 90 percent 
accurate he said a possible diagnosis is about 70 percent accurate 
tests include memory checks brain scans and spinal taps 
physicians also interview the patients family about changes in 
behavior phelps said 
symptoms include memory loss confusion difficulty in judgment 
changes in mood and personality and loss of bodily functions in the 
final stages a patient may be as helpless as a newborn unable to 
recognize relatives 
dr norman foster professor of neurology at the university of 
michigan base for the michigan alzheimers disease research center 
said it takes at least a week and often a month to check brain 
tissue under a microscope for the tangled clumps of cells common in 
alzheimers patients 
foster said physicians usually call on counselors in alzheimers 
cases 
the physicians are not really prepared to handle all the legal 
social and economic ramifications by this illness foster said 
alzheimers support groups were shaken at the news of kevorkians 
machine 
we have a number of services available that would hopefully 
prevent this kind of decision from taking place said manning of 
the support group here we would hope that they explore other 
avenues 
foster said people with alzheimers shouldnt feel so 
hopeless theres lots of things they can do we dont promise 
an instant cure but were attacking this disease 
advances in testing are encouraging said robert p lisak wayne 
state university neurology chairman and chief neurologist at detroit 
medical center and harper hospital 
the newest test measures a protein believed associated with 
alzheimers a study in wednesdays journal of the american medical 
association said the protein can be used as a model for a diagnostic 
test in spinal fluid 
breakthroughs dont come like a bolt out of the blue lisak 
said no one person is going to make a sudden discovery modern 
science builds on it 
at this point you want to make sure its not something 
treatable and then you can kind of say its probably alzheimers 
</TEXT>
