<TEXT>
an oil tanker ran aground thursday spilling 
260000 gallons of heating oil into a busy shipping channel between 
new jersey and new york and the first mate was arrested for 
substance abuse 
it was the fifth major oil spill in the area since january 
footballsize globs of oil washed ashore on both sides of the 
kill van kull waterway which was closed to ships after the tanker 
bt nautilus hit bottom while docking thursday morning bathing 
beaches on new jerseys atlantic shore werent expected to be 
affected officials said 
the first mate identified in court documents as gregory 
frederick geoffrey 52 of merkse england pleaded innocent 
thursday night to charges of operating a vessel under the influence 
of alcohol or drugs and negligent discharge of a pollutant without a 
permit 
his attorney richard f x regan said after the evening 
arraignment it appears that my client is really a scapegoat at 
this point in time for what appears to be an accident 
christopher florentz a spokesman for attorney general robert j 
del tufo said he didnt know if geoffrey was accused of using 
alcohol or drugs officials didnt immediately disclose what role 
geoffrey had in guiding the tanker 
bayonne municipal court judge frank t carpenter iii set bail at 
50000 and ordered the ship to surrender geoffreys passport 
drug tests were ordered for other ship workers and the harbor 
pilot who was on board to help steer the ship to dock 
oil leaked for almost five hours from the ship which was 
carrying 12 million gallons of heating fuel said coast guard rear 
adm richard rybacki in boston 
divers found a gash about 30 feet long and 12 to 16 inches wide 
in one of the ships tanks rybacki said the tank holds 12 million 
gallons 
new york lt gov stan lundine after a helicopter tour of the 
area with new york environmental conservation commissioner thomas 
jorling called the spill serious 
there are areas on beaches and in coves which are clearly 
contaminated with this very heavy oil he said 
the recent rash of spills in kill van kull and connecting arthur 
kill have brought harsh criticism of the oil industry from 
environmentalists and state officials the waterways separate new 
jersey from new yorks staten island and lie along a heavily 
industrialized area 
new york attorney general robert abrams said his office was 
conducting civil and criminal investigations into the spill 
coast guard chief petty officer gene hoff said booms were strung 
around the ship to contain the floating oil vacuum and skimming 
equipment were being used to clean up the slick and up to 300 
workers were expected to use rakes shovels and absorbent material 
to clean the shoreline 
it looks like mud really disgusting said margaret capuana 
of jersey city who went to a park at the southern tip of bayonne to 
see the crippled tanker 
the tanker is owned by nautilus motor tanker of gibraltar and 
operated by bulk tanker management of london the vessel is 
registered in hong kong 
richard bartha a rutgers university microbiology professor said 
the waterways have suffered such environmental destruction in recent 
months that only birds were likely to suffer serious harm 
there is little living in the water anymore because the water 
quality is so bad he said 
thursdays spill prompted new york and new jersey members of 
congress to ask that house speaker thomas foley add a proposal to 
require double hulls on oil tankers into an oil spill bill being 
considered by a housesenate committee 
the waterways have been plagued with major oil spills this year 
on jan 12 567000 gallons of oil leaked into the arthur kill 
from a ruptured exxon underwater pipeline 
on feb 28 30000 gallons of heating oil spilled into the kill 
van kull from a barge anchored in bayonne a day later nearly 4000 
gallons of heavy crude oil spilled into the arthur kill at exxons 
refinery in linden 
about a week later more than 100000 gallons of heating oil was 
dumped in the arthur kill near linden from a barge that exploded and 
caught fire 
