<TEXT>
because of the shelling judges seldom 
hold people in jail awaiting trial but artillery fire also keeps 
judges and lawyers away from work so an accused can wait a long 
time for his day in court 
murder burglary and other crimes still are against the law after 
15 years of ruinous civil war but the battle often overruns what 
remains of the criminal justice system 
months of fighting trapped about 420 prisoners being held on 
charges of murder theft and drug trafficking the showdown between 
christian factions led by gen michel aoun and samir geagea has 
taken nearly 1000 lives and wounded more than 2500 people since 
jan 30 
a lawyer who fled to moslem west beirut said judicial authorities 
were unable to meet to consider dozens of cases of people awaiting 
prosecution for common crimes 
they were arrested and jailed and now their fate depends on 
the situation said the lawyer 
the palace of justice where the meetings normally are held is 
on the confrontation line between geageas areas of influence and 
aouns terrain it is subject to constant sniper fire and shelling 
we have been trying to form a committee to meet anywhere in 
order to take a decision to release the prisoners on bail pending a 
trial when security conditions permit said the judge who 
demanded anonymity like the others interviewed 
i switched on the tv one night and saw gunmen sniping from my 
office at the palace of justice we obviously cannot meet there 
according to the lawyer some colleagues paid quick visits to the 
palace of justice to hide or remove files but it is not possible 
to operate normally from there 
the jails are in the most heavily shelled areas of roumieh 
baabda and furn elshubbak all held by aoun the judge said 
roumieh prison is the biggest aouns main howitzer batteries are 
deployed in a wooded valley around it partially protected from 
geageas fire 
the prisons are so crowded and in such dangerous areas that 
whenever we can meet we try to release most of the detainees who 
have committed minor offenses on bail set at a minimal amount the 
judge said 
we also have no wards to treat drug addicts so again we tend 
to set them free on bail because if we place them in prison theyll 
be more corrupted by other prisoners 
few jails have bomb shelters and the guards generally flee when 
shelling starts 
about fifty inmates escaped from a prison in moslem west beirut 
last year when artillery fire knocked down cell walls during aouns 
sixmonth battle with syrian soldiers and their moslem allies only 
about 30 were caught 
the christian feud has stopped family visits to prisoners and 
telephones went dead months ago 
the lack of security also means prisoners could receive 
visitors only during lulls in the fighting the judge said 
those who have family and friends in geageacontrolled areas 
havent had visitors since the clashes began 
the judge said some prisoners who finished their terms might be 
safer in jail but were not allowed to stay 
if they are known to have been geagea supporters before they 
were imprisoned theyre in trouble for the prisons are in an area 
under aouns control he said 
