<TEXT>
ever since adam clayton powell the flamboyant 
playboypreacher from harlem was driven from his house seat in 
1967 black leaders have seen a conspiracy at work 
for years theyve said that the white power structure singles out 
any black politician who threatens the status quo and some who 
dont for relentless investigation and costly prosecution 
washington mayor marion barry jr on trial on drug and perjury 
charges after an elaborate fbi sting they say is just the latest 
victim of selective prosecution 
attorney general dick thornburgh denies that government 
prosecutors targeted barry or that they go after black politicians 
we follow the evidence wherever it leads regardless of 
position race party affiliation or other identifying factors 
thornburgh said in january he was responding to benjamin hooks 
executive director of the naacp who pictured barry as a victim of 
selective law enforcement 
hooks remains unconvinced in an interview he estimated that 80 
percent of the black people in washington share the perception that 
barry has been singled out 
us attorney jay stephens suggested that the government paid 
extraordinary attention to the barry case after years of rumors 
that he was using drugs because as mayor barry was a role model 
for the black youth of washington 
in court stephens called barrys arrest a personal tragedy for 
the defendant but added narcotics abuse is also a tragedy for 
this city narcotics abuse is not a victimless crime 
the issue of whether barry had been singled out because of his 
race came to dominate the jury selection process last week at his 
trial 
judge thomas penfield jackson asked prospective jurors if they 
believe the law is selectively enforced many of the blacks said 
they did 
it seems like some people are made to go through a little more 
than others said one a gospel singer they televised this too 
much talked about it too much i think race had a lot to do 
with it as far as giving him a hard time 
the judge asked if a white mayor would have been spared 
prosecution under similar circumstances 
exactly she said 
the masses of the people out there understand what is going 
on says clarence mitchell iii former maryland state legislator 
and onetime colleague with barry in the 1960s civil rights 
organization the student nonviolent coordinating committee 
the media can say barrys lifestyle is not appropriate but the 
masses of people perceive that if marion barry were white we would 
not be reading anything about him says mitchell 
mitchell says he too became a victim of selective prosecution 
as he was running in a primary for the nomination to a congressional 
seat vacated by his uncle parren mitchell 
mitchell lost the nomination he and his brother michael 
scions of a prominent black family and son of civil rights leader 
clarence mitchell jr were subsequently convicted of taking a 
bribe to block an investigation by parren mitchells house small 
business committee 
at the sentencing their mother juanita jackson mitchell 
alluded to their claim that they were victims of an fbi vendetta 
against black leaders 
my sons are casualties on the road to freedom she said 
thus say black leaders the mitchells joined a long list of 
black politicians who had been singled out 
on the list mayors maynard jackson of atlanta coleman young of 
detroit and richard arrington of birmingham ala former mayors 
carl stokes of cleveland kenneth gibson of newark nj and 
charles evers of fayette miss reps charles rangel dny 
harold ford dtenn and louis stokes dohio and former reps 
shirley chisholm dny and charles diggs dmich 
hooks says if they had accused barry of stealing millions 
creating a slush fund awarding corrupt contracts that would be one 
thing but a personal habit that is bad dangerous lethal that 
makes him a bad role model there are 4 million people out there 
doing it if there are 4 million why did they pick out one and 
stick on his case for eight years 
hooks is careful to say he is not passing judgment on barrys 
guilt or innocence instead he draws an analogy if everyone is 
going 80 miles an hour on the highway and youre doing 70 and the 
cops stop you youve got to wonder 
what im trying to say is the perception is there he says 
and the government has a right to dispel the perception if it 
isnt true 
adds joann watson who heads the national ywcas office of racial 
justice we are not supporting quote corrupt politicians 
joseph agne consultant to the national council of churches says 
he sees a motive behind selective prosecution this is one way to 
get around the gains from the voting rights act whose enactment 
raised the number of black elected officials from the scores to the 
thousands 
but lawyer richard a samp chief counsel for the conservative 
washington legal foundation says prosecutors lack the resources to 
bring charges against every lawbreaker he says it makes sense for 
them to focus first on officeholders 
blacks arent singled out he says but since there is likely to 
be more corruption at the local level and given that much of the 
black electoral success to date has been at the local level it is 
perhaps not surprising that blacks have been included among the 
targets of these corruption probes 
and louis michael seidman law professor at georgetown 
university points to a 19th century supreme court decision that 
selective prosecution of prominent wealthy people on tax charges 
for example is permissible as long as it is not based on such 
things as race or religion 
now that barry has admitted he used crack cocaine at the vista 
hotel on jan 18 his only recourse is to persuade a jury that he 
was unfairly singled out says seidman 
in reality that is his defense says seidman 
barry seemed to be saying as much when he told the washington 
post on may 28 i think the prosecutors know that in this town all 
it takes is one juror saying im not going to convict marion 
barry i dont care what you say 
mary r sawyer assistant professor of religious studies at iowa 
state university in ames has been studying the question of 
selective prosecution for years 
what is happening to black elected officials today is only 
marginally different from what happened to black activists in the 
black power and black civil right eras and to what happened to 
blacks during jim crow segregation days and what happened to blacks 
during slavery ms sawyer said 
in each instance the leaders were singled out there was a 
double standard there were steps taken to intimidate and terminate 
effective strategies for social change 
