<TEXT>
plans to involve the army in fighting 
drugs which the united states supports have many bolivians worried 
that a largely peaceful lawenforcement effort will become a bloody 
war like the one in colombia 
proponents say only the military can control the vast lawless 
areas where cocaine traffickers now operate with impunity 
few shots have been fired in bolivias campaign against 
narcotics and bloodshed is rare 
a specially trained 600man police unit called the leopards 
works closely with the us drug enforcement administration in 
pursuing processors and traffickers growers of coca the base of 
cocaine are urged to switch crops voluntarily 
during a trip to washington in may however president jaime paz 
zamora agreed to commit about 900 soldiers in two army battalions to 
the effort and to increase air force and navy involvement 
in return bolivia will get 75 million worth of us military 
equipment and training during 199091 
paz zamora kept the agreement quiet preferring to emphasize 127 
million in economic aid pledged by the united states in the same 
twoyear period but it was leaked to the la paz newspaper 
presencia publication inspired protests from opposition politicians 
and labor unions 
presencia quoted jorge alderrete a former undersecretary of the 
interior as saying the government has put at risk all the 
countrys chances to achieve a peaceful solution to the drug 
trafficking problem it will do nothing more than prove an old 
axiom violence begets violence 
alderrete is a prominent member of the revolutionary nationalist 
movement the main political opposition 
bolivias army is better known for coups detat and corruption 
than combat skills a military government that took power in 1980 
even worked closely with cocaine traffickers 
the army also has a reputation for heavyhandedness when it is 
called in to put down strikes for instance bloodshed often results 
cocagrowing peasants militant and well organized have sworn 
they will resist any any military crackdown 
leading officers of the leopards also question the switch to a 
military approach 
maj carlos barriga leopard commander for the beni region said 
he would accept whatever help he could get but that army 
involvement can create big social problems weve had some 
experiences in the past 
the armed forces is an institution created to defend 
sovereignty from an exterior threat barriga said in an interview 
in trinidad capital of the beni i think the situation is being 
basically controlled now without violence 
the beni is an expanse of jungles and grasslands about the size 
of texas loaded with clandestine cocaine laboratories 
barriga said leopard and dea operations there had done a lot of 
damage to the traffickers he cited the discovery of 18 labs and 
10 important drug caches during 1989 
don ferrarone dea attache for bolivia said the most pressing 
need was additional transport and communications equipment so more 
leopards could take part in raids he said only about two dozen 
could be deployed for an operation by air because of shortages of 
planes and helicopters 
the first thing we need to attend to is fully applying the 
people we have out here he told the associated press in trinidad 
where he was directing helicopter and boat raids were not in a 
declared war and we have to take a stepbystep approach to applying 
the military 
those who favor military involvement including us ambassador 
robert gelbard say army action is needed if bolivia is going to 
nip in the bud what is developing into a real national threat 
cocaine traffickers operate beyond the laws reach in eastern and 
northern bolivia they are believed to control entire towns that 
police and us drug agents wont enter for fear of attack by 
townspeople 
we have to find ways to cover these areas gelbard said in an 
interview in la paz bolivia is no longer just a producer of 
coca leaf and paste it is now is a major producer of cocaine 
hydrochloride if the problem is ignored im afraid it really could 
become another colombia 
gelbard noted that some air force units have been involved in the 
antidrug effort for years flying a dozen vietnamera huey 
helicopters supplied by the united states the navy also interdicts 
drugs on jungle rivers 
some bolivian critics draw parallels between escalating the drug 
war and the us involvement in vietnam expressing concern about 
the increasing number of us advisers and trainers in bolivia 
to that argument gelbard responds you need advisers and 
trainers to avoid the problems other countries have had where 
charred carcasses of us helicopters lie in the valleys 
he said us training had produced a corps of bolivian air force 
helicopter pilots that was the best in latin america 
more than 100 us civilian and military officials are involved 
in the antinarcotics campaign 
green beret trainers run a base in the chapare cocagrowing 
region 
us army navy and air force advisers work with dea agents and 
the leopards us border patrol agents and a special coast guard 
unit carry out interdiction operations on roads and rivers 
some us civilian personnel such as dea coast guard and border 
patrol agents are allowed to take part in raids but american 
military personnel are limited to training and advising 
