coca farmers who agreed to switch crops 
waited hours to sign up for the government eradication program two 
months for officials to certify their coca plants had been destroyed 
and several weeks to be paid 
samuel zambrana 61 with seven children said he was going along 
with the plan but i have no income now and i cannot get my banana 
and orange crop out because of bad roads if the government is going 
to take coca away from us we need profitable alternative crops 
good roads and a market 
since dec 1 farmers have destroyed a record 4500 hectares of 
coca more than onetenth of the 38250 devoted to growing the crop 
from which cocaine is made according to us government figures a 
hectare is about 2 acres 
we continue to be very pleased with voluntary eradication 
programs and the commitment which the bolivian government continues 
to demonstrate the us embassy said 
tens of thousands of farmers have left the chapare cocaproducing 
region because of a sharp drop in prices for the leaf farmers 
receive 2000 from the bolivian government for every hectare 
destroyed 
voluntary eradication was spurred late last year when colombias 
drug war and increased interdiction in bolivia disrupted cocaine 
production and reduced the demand for coca leaves 
a 100pound sack of coca costs about 30 to produce and brought 
only 10 at the beginning of may compared with 100 five years ago 
but had risen to about 20 by the end of the month the increase 
caused concern that cocaine processing operations were resuming in 
colombia 
nearly onethird of the worlds coca leaves are produced in the 
chapare a lush tropical region in the heart of bolivia 
at least 300000 farmers depend on coca cultivation and cocaine 
production for a livelihood the government says the industry brings 
about 600 million a year into the economy 
leaves of the coca bush which resemble bay leaves are harvested 
four times a year dried and then macerated into paste with kerosene 
in plasticcovered pits the paste is refined into cocaine in labs 
in the bolivian lowlands colombia and brazil 
bolivia which has a population of 71 million is south 
americas poorest country and its largest recipient of us aid 
