<TEXT>
heinrich schliemann the 19thcentury 
german archaeologist credited with discovering the legendary city of 
troy has come under fresh attack a century after his death 
more than 200 archaeologists historians and classicists gathered 
in athens to mark schliemanns death and debate the legacy of the 
man considered the father of prehistoric greek archaeology 
schliemann a grocers son who became a millionaire is famous 
for excavating the ancient cities of troy and mycenae and finding 
bronze age civilizations at the sites whose existence previously was 
unknown 
but some experts have doubted schliemanns integrity and the 
reliability of the historical data he left his successors 
my findings seem to show that schliemann was a pathological 
liar david a taill a classics professor at the university of 
california at davis said in an interview 
controversy has surrounded schliemanns findings since their 
publication in 1874 his methods primitive by todays standards 
have often been criticized 
still many historians regard him as a pioneer in archaeological 
discovery and say purported inaccuracies may be due to hasty 
documentation 
taill who spoke at the conference held last month spent 10 
years scouring records of schliemanns excavations as well as his 
diaries and letters 
the professor said the value of an archaeological find depended 
on knowing where particular pieces were discovered placement often 
indicates age 
once it has been established schliemann falsified some of his 
finds the question is how great is the damage he said 
the implications of any faking could be great for example his 
data on the existence of settlements and the position of objects at 
troy have helped to determine the age of ruins throughout the 
anatolia region in turkey troy is in modernday hissarlik turkey 
taill and others have challenged schliemanns most dramatic 
discovery a gold hoard he said was the treasure of legendary king 
priam 
im fairly convinced he found some of the items separately and 
put them together for a big bang at the end taill said taill 
claimed that schliemann in different accounts changed his 
description of where he found priams treasure 
schliemanns account of finding the treasure with his wife 
sophia was false because letters showed she was in athens at the 
time taill said 
taills research added new fuel to a debate that has raged for 
years schliemanns excavating techniques have long been debated 
with some people saying he destroyed valuable data by working too 
quickly 
another expert edmund f bloedow professor of ancient history 
at ottawa university told conference delegates that differences in 
schliemanns accounts could be attributed to the inevitable haste 
in making initial notes and sketches and transcribing them 
professor manfred korfmann of tubingen university in west germany 
said schliemann may have enlarged the king priam trove with items he 
bought but korfmann who is excavating at troy nonetheless 
emphasized schliemanns pioneering of archaeological techniques 
questions about king priams hoard may never be resolved 
schliemann said he found the gold silver and bronze trove in 1873 
he gave it to germany and during world war ii it was stored in a 
berlin vault it later vanished 
schliemann is esteemed for using archaeology as a means to 
reconstruct historical periods 
before him archaeologists generally dug to find sculptures to 
enrich private and museum collections schliemanns attention to 
small finds at different levels of the earth resulted in a more 
accurate method of determining chronologies 
with the publication of schliemanns first reports on troy 
archaeology and prehistoric field archaeology in particular began 
to move ahead toward something entirely new korfmann told the 
delegates 
taill to underline his contention that schliemanns integrity 
was dubious listed examples of how the archaeologist had allegedly 
lied in his personal life 
he claimed that schliemann gained us citizenship in 1869 by 
lying about the length of his stay in the country 
schliemann also apparently falsified his diary taill said a 
june 1851 entry gives his graphic eyewitness account of a major 
fire in san francisco however the fire was in may when schliemann 
was in sacramento taill said 
why would he lie in his own diary he asked 
despite attacks on schliemanns credibility scholars admired his 
skills 
schliemann who died dec 26 1890 at 68 immersed himself in 
the poet homer schliemann said he found troy by following homers 
descriptions of its location 
however historians point out that hissarlik had already been 
suggested as the likely site of prehistoric troy 
</TEXT>
