<TEXT>
us businesses plan to boost plant and 
equipment investment in 1990 at the slowest rate in three years the 
government said thursday the report reflected a sluggish economy 
and weak product demand 
the commerce department said a survey completed in may found 
businesses planning to boost spending on expansion and modernization 
by 55 percent to 5004 billion it would be the fourth consecutive 
yearly increase 
but while the spending projection would top the record 4743 
billion set last year the rate of increase would be the slowest 
since a 42 percent gain in 1987 investments rose 89 percent last 
year and 94 percent in 1988 
it shows the manufacturing sector is responding negatively to 
the sluggishness in that area said robert g dederick chief 
economist for the northern trust co in chicago 
all one is looking for here is that it not be a drag on the 
economy he added if it were a drag it would be a heavy burden 
on the economy given the other negatives such as defense spending 
and housing 
manufacturing and housing have been the sectors of the economy 
hardest hit by the federal reserves tightmoney policy also the 
federal government has cut back on military spending because of 
budget constraints 
the new estimate is down from the 79 percent spending increase 
in a previous survey completed in march a survey completed in 
november indicated a 49 percent investment gain this year 
all of the figures have been adjusted for inflation 
lawrence chimerine senior economic adviser for the wefa group in 
bala cynwyd pa said three factors were dampening investment plans 
a soft economy and subsequent sluggish demand weak profits and 
cash flows and high interest rates and tighter restrictions on 
credit 
the only thing keeping capital spending going now is the fact a 
lot of companies realize if they dont modernize and improve 
productivity and improve the quality of their products theyll be 
out of business eventually he said 
replacing aging plants and equipment and expanding facilities 
helps to boost us productivity an increasingly important factor 
in view of the stiff competition american companies face from 
overseas 
the labor department reported monday that american worker 
productivity had plunged at a 27 percent annual rate so far this 
year the poorest showing since the 198182 recession 
any growth in business spending would help stimulate the economy 
now in its eighth year of expansion and pick up some of the slack 
from diminished consumer spending 
before adjusting for inflation the department survey projected a 
67 percent increase for all businesses this year to 5072 billion 
after gains of 104 percent last year and 105 percent in 1988 
it said the investment increase for all industries includes a 34 
percent gain for manufacturing firms and an 87 percent advance for 
companies engaged in mining transportation and other 
nonmanufacturing activities 
manufacturers are projecting investment spending this year of 
1909 billion the anticipated rate of increase is lower than the 
average for all industries and down from the 49 percent projection 
in april 
the manufacturing gain includes a 24 percent hike in durable 
goods bigticket items expected to last at least three years and 
a 43 percent increase in nondurables 
