<TEXT>
manuel h johnson unexpectedly announced his 
resignation thursday from the no 2 job at the federal reserve 
creating a key opening at an agency often criticized by the bush 
administration for keeping interest rates too high 
johnson 41 said he planned to return to an academic career 
the aug 3 departure will give president bush the chance to make 
another appointment to the sevenmember board that directs the 
nations monetary policy 
the administration at various times in past months has been 
openly critical of the feds efforts to restrain inflation by 
keeping interest rates high 
there was a published report in march quoting an unnamed bush 
adviser as saying the president was mad as hell with federal 
reserve chairman alan greenspan and would not reappoint him as 
chairman 
bush later insisted there was no bubbling war with greenspan 
but left the clear impression he would like to see more aggressive 
action on the part of the fed to lower interest rates 
analysts said it was likely that bush would appoint someone to 
the fed who would be more amenable to the administrations pleas for 
lower interest rates 
this administration has been jawboning the fed on and off for 
some time for a looser monetary policy said kenneth guenther of 
the independent bankers association of america they want lower 
interest rates because they dont want the economy moving into a 
recession 
fed officials have been pursuing a softlanding approach for 
the economy in which interest rates are used to slow growth enough 
to ease inflationary pressures but not enough to tip the country 
into a recession 
many analysts believe that approach is working and that the fed 
is unlikely to change course even with a new vice chairman appointed 
by bush 
the fed isnt closely divided now where one vote in either 
direction would make much of a difference said lyle gramley a 
former fed governor and now chief economist of the mortgage bankers 
association 
the white house would not discuss possible successors but deputy 
white house press secretary alixe glen said the administration 
believed johnson had done a terrific job 
bush will may either name someone new to the board and designate 
that person vice chairman or select one of the other governors as 
vice chairman while appointing someone to fill johnsons board term 
which runs until aug 21 2000 
there was speculation that david mullins appointed to the fed 
earlier this year might be considered for the vice chairmans job 
mullins one of the authors of the savings and loan bailout 
legislation had been a top assistant to treasury secretary nicholas 
brady 
others mentioned as possible candidates for appointment were 
wendy gramm head of the commodity futures trading commission and 
wife of sen phil gramm rtexas john taylor a member of the 
presidents council of economic advisers and treasury under 
secretary robert glauber 
the administration is likely to choose someone out of the same 
mold as mullins said david jones author of a book on the federal 
reserve and chief economist at aubrey g lanston amp co he will be 
a proadministration republican with an academic background 
johnson had once been considered a top candidate to become fed 
chairman if the administration chose not to reappoint greenspan next 
year 
johnson said at a news conference that he fully backed the 
reappointment of greenspan and that policy disagreements were not a 
factor in his decision to step down 
while past fed governors have cited the low pay as a reason for 
resigning johnson said his 82500 salary was not a factor in his 
decision 
the main reason i decided to step down is that i have spent 10 
consecutive years in public service he said ten years is long 
enough 
johnson was appointed to the fed by president reagan on feb 7 
1986 and was elevated to vice chairman six months later 
he said his resignation would be effective at the end of his 
fouryear term as vice chairman 
i am extremely proud to have played a part in the unprecedented 
period of sustained economic growth and low inflation that has 
characterized the decade of the 1980s and continues into the 
1990s johnson said in his letter of resignation 
johnson said he planned to return to george mason university in 
washingtons virginia suburbs and assume the koch chair in 
international economics and become director of the center for global 
market studies 
he was a professor at the school in 1981 when he was selected to 
join the economics team assembled by thentreasury secretary donald 
regan in reagans first term 
i deeply regret but understand manley johnsons decision 
greenspan said in a statement the vice chairman and i have been 
an effective team ill miss him 
the fed the nations central bank headquartered in washington 
is run by the board of governors and a nationwide network of 12 
district banks the governors are appointed by the president and 
confirmed by the senate to serve 14year terms 
</TEXT>
