<TEXT>
trans world airlines chairman carl icahn has 
disclosed plans to sell 20 boeing 727s in what union officials 
called another scare tactic in his bid to gain concessions from 
pilots 
icahn has promised to modernize twas fleet if pilots take 10 
percent pay cuts and agree to other concessions that would save 80 
million a year he has threatened to shrink or dismantle the 
troubled carrier if they refuse 
kent scott chairman of the twa branch of the air line pilots 
association said wednesday that icahn may only be trying to get rid 
of the old relatively inefficient jets to make room for more modern 
ones such as europeanmade airbuses 
of course he wouldnt let us in on that scott said hed 
make it look like a liquidation to put more pressure on us 
thomas albrecht an analyst for ag edwards said he also 
doubted that the sale of the planes was the beginning of a 
dismantling of the airline he said icahn would probably make no 
drastic changes as long as he still saw a chance of selling the 
entire airline to employees or an outside buyer 
ive got to believe that if he was going to shrink the airline 
he wouldnt be doing it now albrecht said he still wants to 
keep it attractive 
the plan to sell the jets was disclosed this week when icahn sent 
out solicitations for bids to avmark an airline marketing and 
consulting company 
the current plan is different from earlier sales analysts say 
twa has sold 21 other jets since december in deals that generated 
about 580 million in proceeds all but two of those jets were 
leased back to the airline however 
the current sale of jets is apparently an attempt to eliminate 
the 727s from the carriers 210jet fleet 
it does not look like a saleleaseback type of arrangement 
said paul turk an analyst for avmark 
twa and other airlines have been selling and leasing back jets to 
capitalize on a strong market for used aircraft used 727s of the 
type that twa is selling have been bringing anywhere from 65 
million to 12 million turk said 
twa could replace the 727s by leasing or buying some of the 100 
airbus a320s once destined for braniff inc which went bankrupt 
last fall 
