<TEXT>
the two broadest measures of the nations money 
supply fell in the week ended may 28 the federal reserve board 
reported thursday 
the fed said the measure known as m2 fell to a seasonally 
adjusted 32586 billion from 32664 billion the previous week 
an even broader measure m3 fell to a seasonally adjusted 
40526 billion from 40634 billion 
the narrowest measure of the money supply m1 fell to a 
seasonally adjusted 8037 billion from 8069 billion 
m1 includes cash in circulation deposits in checking accounts 
and nonbank travelers checks m2 is m1 plus accounts like savings 
deposits and moneymarket mutual funds m3 is m2 plus lessliquid 
accounts such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations 
of 100000 
in judging its monetary policy the fed has indicated it is 
monitoring the value of the dollar commodity prices and the 
difference between short and longterm interest rates it also has 
shifted its attention from m1 to the two broader money supply 
measures 
the annual growth rate in m2 so far this year is 35 percent 
which is within the feds target range of 3 percent to 7 percent 
the annual growth rate in m3 was 11 percent below the feds target 
range of 25 percent to 65 percent the fed has not set a target 
for m1 growth since early 1987 
for the latest 13 weeks m2 averaged 32680 billion a 44 
percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous 13 
weeks m3 averaged 40652 billion up 16 percent while m1 rose 
46 percent to an average of 8057 billion 
in other reports 
the federal reserve bank of new york reported commercial and 
industrial loans at major new york city banks fell 172 million 
compared with a decline of 1157 billion a week earlier 
the federal reserve said bank borrowings from the federal 
reserve system at the discount window excluding extended credit 
averaged 442 million a day in the week ended wednesday down from 
924 million the previous week 
the federal reserve said net free reserves averaged 401 million 
in the two weeks ended may 30 down from 645 million in the 
previous twoweek period 
the federal reserve bank of st louis reported that the monetary 
base the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at 
federal reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation 
was 3050 billion in the twoweek period ended may 30 down from 
3060 billion two weeks earlier 
