<TEXT>
plants in the petrochemical and industrial 
belts of louisiana and texas release the most toxic industrial 
chemicals but pockets of significant toxic pollution exist across 
the nation a private group said thursday 
nearly every state in the nation has become a dumping ground 
for toxic chemicals by the nations largest manufacturers said 
robert brandon vice president of citizen action 
citizen action a washingtonbased environmental and consumer 
group said that jefferson parish and st charles parish in 
louisiana and sedgwick county in kansas had the largest releases of 
toxic industrial chemicals in 1988 
all three areas have major chemical companies and industrial 
plants that use large amounts of solvents 
the organization used statistics published earlier this year by 
the environmental protection agency compiled from annual reports by 
industrial plants to the agency 
according to the epa 46 billion pounds of toxic chemicals were 
released by industry into the air water and into the ground in 
1988 the latest year for which data were available the epa has 
said it could not estimate the resulting health risks because it has 
no information on the extent of human exposure to the chemicals 
citizen action gave the total as 62 billion pounds the group 
included 16 billion pounds sent away for disposal or to municipal 
treatment facilities the epa does not consider the 16 billion 
pounds to have been released into the environment 
of the total releases cited by citizen action about half of the 
chemicals were released in 10 states louisana texas ohio 
indiana illinois tennessee michigan california pennsylvania and 
florida 
major toxic polluters however were found in many parts of the 
country 
the eastman kodak co was the second largest source of 
cancercausing emissions the group said its complex of plants in 
rochester ny released more than 97 million pounds of 
cancercausing chemicals the company in the past has said the 
releases are not a health hazard 
the 3m corp a minneapolisbased manufacturer of a variety of 
products such as recording tape and sandpaper led the list of 
companies releasing chemicals that may be linked to birth defects 
it released 53 million pounds of such chemicals including 16 
million pounds from a plant in hutchinson minn the group said 
rick renner a 3m corp spokesman said the company has an 
extensive pollution control effort underway and the 1988 figures do 
not reflect new controls as some of the companys factories our 
emissions will be down substantially this year he said 
sedgwick county in kansas containing wichita was the third most 
polluted county on the list largely because of vulcan chemicals 
which has a plant there and the widespread use of solvents at a 
boeing co plant 
vulcans releases are mostly through the injection of chemical 
wastes into deep wells industry says such releases are a safe 
disposal method but environmentalists say they could threaten 
groundwater 
southern california ranked high on emissions largely because of a 
concentration of petrochemical plastics aerospace and other 
industrial plants the environmental group said 
citizen action is a washingtonbased federation of consumer and 
environmental groups in 27 states and claims more than 2 million 
members 
spokesmen for the chemical manufacturers association simply noted 
that the citizen action report was based on data that had been made 
public previously the industry group in the past has acknowledged 
that toxic releases from chemical plants are too high and says its 
member companies are working to reduce them 
