<TEXT>
the government boosted its efforts to stem the 
dollars rise against the japanese yen from february through april 
but by the end of the quarter it was market sentiment that actually 
stopped the climb the federal reserve said thursday 
the fed and the us treasury sold 178 million in the three 
months ended april 30 nearly 90 percent of it to buy yen the fed 
said in its quarterly foreign exchange report the remaining 200 
million was used to buy west german marks 
in the previous three months october through january the 
government spent 750 million intervening in currency markets all 
of it to buy yen 
although purchases more than doubled in the latest quarter it 
was far far lower than the earlier threemonth period last 
year sam y cross a fed executive vice president who released 
the report at a press conference 
the governments purchases last year included a record 1192 
billion in yen and marks during the three months ended july 31 and 
5871 billion in the following three months 
the dollar rose 10 percent against the yen during the 
februaryapril period this year while declining by less than 05 
percent against the mark 
the dollar saw its steepest climb of the period against the yen 
from late february through early april the climb subsided as the 
market awaited the april 7 meeting of financial officials from 
governments of the socalled group of seven leading industrial 
nations the fed said 
also in april the market came to view the bank of japans 1 
percent increase in its discount rate as sufficient to lessen 
downward pressure on the yen then the japanese stock and bond 
markets began to recoup some of their losses according to the 
report 
the dollar hit a low for the period of 1436 yen on feb 19 but 
began to rally after election victories for the liberal democratic 
party in japan and predictions that interest rates outside japan 
could rise further weakening the yen the government sold 650 
million to buy yen between february 23 and march 2 
also fears that german inflation would accelerate due to the 
pending currency union between east and west germany strengthened 
the dollar against the mark it reached 17237 marks on march 1 
between march 5 and march 27 the treasury sold 830 million to 
buy yen and sold 200 million for marks the purchases were made by 
the us treasury as the fed temporarily put its intervention 
program on hold the fed and treasury normally split the funds used 
for intervention 
the temporary halt in intervention came after some fed officials 
said they were concerned that high amounts of purchases like those 
in 1989 could cause doubts about the feds commitment to curbing 
inflation according to the report 
the governments currencyintervention programs can have the 
unintended effect of increasing the supply of dollars and some 
feared inflation could result 
furthermore the feds holdings of foreign currencies were 
approaching the 21 billion authorized by the federal open market 
committee the fed decided to stop making purchases until the 
committees march 27 meeting where an additional 4 billion in 
holdings were authorized also the fomc decided to retain 
tightmoney policies 
the government intervened twice more on march 28 and april 9 
selling 50 million for yen each time 
