<TEXT>
martin s davis chairman of paramount 
communications inc testified thursday that ivan boesky in 1985 
doggedly pursued a leveraged buyout of paramounts predecessor gulf 
amp western industries inc and threatened a takeover fight 
despite repeated rejections boesky did not accept no as an 
answer davis said at the federal securities fraud trial of former 
boesky associate john a mulheren jr 
the more we said no the more he asked us to think about it so 
in order to facilitate his leaving we said wed think about it 
davis testified under questioning from assistant us attorney e 
scott gilbert 
mulheren 40 is accused of inflating the stock price of gulf amp 
western to 45 in october 1985 by purchasing 75000 shares to help 
boesky make more money in selling his stake back to the company 
boesky who previously testified at the trial paid 100 million 
in penalties and pleaded guilty to one felony to settle the biggest 
insider trading case ever in exchange he gave government 
investigators incriminating information about several associates 
including mulheren 
davis said he first met with boesky on sept 5 1985 amid rumors 
and media reports that boesky and others were contemplating a 
takeover of gulf amp western after it sold off its manufacturing and 
textile holdings for 1 billion in cash 
at the meeting attended and arranged by investor carl icahn 
davis said boesky told him he held 49 percent of gulf amp westerns 
stock and proposed that davis agree to a leveraged buyout at 50 per 
share 
when davis rejected the proposal as ridiculously low boesky 
said he would increase his holdings to 99 percent and then demand 
two seats on the companys board 
davis then chairman of gulf amp western said his response to 
boeksys proposal was an emphatic no 
he said icahn also held 49 percent of the companys stock but 
told him he was not a party to boeskys proposal 
at a second meeting on oct 1 1985 davis said boesky continued 
to persist in his leveraged buyout proposal telling davis he could 
personally earn 100 million to 200 million 
davis testified he told boesky he had no interest in doing 
business with him especially in a plan that he thought would 
disenfranchise shareholders 
boesky then offered to sell back his holdings in gulf amp western 
at 45 per share which was higher than its trading price on the new 
york stock exchange davis said david testified that he said he 
would only buy back the stock at the market price 
davis said he had a telephone conversation with boesky on oct 
16 1985 the night before gulf amp western bought back all 67 
million of boeskys and icahns shares in the company 
he said that during that conversation boesky reiterated his 
buyback offer of 45 per share but that davis rejected it because 
the stock closed that day at just above 44 
the buyback took place on oct 17 when the price of the shares 
rose to 45 davis said 
prosecutors claim mulheren aided boesky in boosting the price of 
the stock by purchasing 75000 shares on oct 17 
davis also testified that mulheren at an oct 3 1985 meeting 
offered help in monitoring boeskys activities in connection with 
gulf amp western 
davis said he made some uncomplimentary statements about boesky 
and that mulheren certainly didnt disagree 
in a later telephone conversation that took place before the 
buyback davis said mulheren told him he didnt believe boesky owned 
any gulf amp western securities davis said mulheren never told him 
about his own purchase of the gulf amp western stock 
in addition to stock manipulation mulheren is charged with 
concealing ownership of other stocks to help boesky cheat on taxes 
and evade federal securities laws 
