<TEXT>
hitachi ltd a leading japanese electric machinery 
maker said it has produced the first prototype of a 64megabit 
memory chip 
the company said the development of the dynamic random access 
memory chip puts it in the lead in the race to produce future 
generations of memory chips which are used in products ranging from 
computers to compact disc players 
the tiny circuits etched in the semiconductor chip are only 03 
microns or millionths of a meter wide the chip can hold about 64 
million binary units of information enough to hold the equivalent 
of 512 english newspaper pages or one hour of music recorded on 
compact discs hitachi spokesman takafumi ichinose said thursday 
that should lead to the development of a variety of new 
products he said 
hitachi expects to begin marketing the chip in 1995 he said 
each generation of memory chips is generally replaced by a new 
generation with four times as much capacity every three years 
the most advanced dram chips currently being marketed have a 
capacity of four megabits 
